<!-- coder.archml — a minimalist tool-calling coding agent (agent-loop.md §7).
     The whole Phase-1 kernel in one screen: the loop (m-agent), the model call
     (m-reason), the seed of the task (m-objective), and one tool (m-terminal).

     Run:
       MEDITATOR_OBJECTIVE="make the failing tests pass" \
         bun meditator.js -a architecture/agents/coder.archml
     The objective may be written inline below instead; MEDITATOR_OBJECTIVE overrides
     it at wake, exactly as MEDITATOR_ORIGIN seeds a mind. Ctrl-C sleeps it gracefully.

     NOTE (local models): m-reason calls the model with tools, so a local vLLM must be
     launched with --enable-auto-tool-choice and a matching --tool-call-parser
     (agent-loop.md §12), the same requirement m-act already has. -->
<m-agent name="coder"
         model="voice"
         utilityModel="utility"
         maxSteps="40"
         stopWhen="no-tools">
  You are a coding agent working inside a sandboxed workspace. Given a task, you
  make it happen: read the code, change it, and run commands to check your work,
  looping until the task is genuinely done. Prefer small, verified steps over big
  guesses. Never claim something works until you have run it and seen it pass.
  When the task is complete and verified, reply with a short summary and no tool
  call.

  <!-- The seed of the WORK, held apart from the charter above — the twin of a
       mind's <m-origin>. Seeds the first `user` turn; overridable at wake with
       MEDITATOR_OBJECTIVE, exactly as MEDITATOR_ORIGIN seeds a mind. -->
  <m-objective name="objective">
    Make the failing tests in this project pass without weakening them.
  </m-objective>

  <!-- The model call. Low temperature, roomy budget for tool-calling turns.
       Swappable: replace with a plan-then-act reasoner and nothing else changes. -->
  <m-reason name="reason" toolTokens="2048" temperature="0.2"></m-reason>

  <!-- The tools. Each bubbles a `capability` event that m-agent catches and offers to
       the reasoner — no registration wiring here, and nothing in m-agent/m-reason
       changes when one is added or removed (agent-loop.md §8). The terminal reuses the
       existing sandbox and, inside an <m-agent>, returns the raw screen as an
       `observation`. read_file / write_file / edit are ~40-line leaf components that
       read and change files inside the agent's workspace, contained to its root. -->
  <m-terminal   name="terminal"   wall="60s" network="off"></m-terminal>
  <m-read-file  name="read_file"></m-read-file>
  <m-write-file name="write_file"></m-write-file>
  <m-edit       name="edit"></m-edit>

  <!-- A pure observer (agent-loop.md §9): it watches the `step` boundary and, when the
       agent runs essentially the same action over and over, first NUDGES it to try
       something different and finally HALTS a genuine rut. One line, no core change —
       the operational twin of a mind's <m-loop-detector>. -->
  <m-repeat-guard nudgeAt="3" haltAt="6"></m-repeat-guard>

  <!-- NOTE: the file tools default to the agent's own workspace home
       (memory/coder/workspace, shared with the terminal). To let the coder work on a
       real project instead, give the tools a root, e.g.
         <m-read-file name="read_file" root="/path/to/project"></m-read-file>

       To watch this agent work in the Studio, add a membrane and it becomes visible in
       the transcript panel (milestone 4): <m-ws name="ws" port="7640"></m-ws> — inbound
       input becomes a task and the loop streams to the panel. (Adding m-ws also turns the
       one-shot into a service that idles for the next task; the objective above still
       seeds the first run.) For now the objective is supplied at wake and progress logged. -->
</m-agent>
